00:00:53.780 --> 00:00:55.570
We've been supported
for two years

00:00:55.570 --> 00:00:57.160
by a Davis Foundation grant.

00:00:57.160 --> 00:00:59.860
The PI on the grant
is Haynes Miller.

00:00:59.860 --> 00:01:03.100
And I classify him as
our PI and visionary,

00:01:03.100 --> 00:01:06.500
because the vision of bringing
active learning into the math

00:01:06.500 --> 00:01:08.970
department was his, and
it takes some effort.

00:01:08.970 --> 00:01:15.550
So thank you for that, and
it's working in some way.

00:01:15.550 --> 00:01:16.889
You'll see.

00:01:16.889 --> 00:01:18.180
Here's the outline of the talk.

00:01:18.180 --> 00:01:19.638
We'll talk about
what we inherited,

00:01:19.638 --> 00:01:24.120
but we came into with
18.05, what we've done,

00:01:24.120 --> 00:01:25.720
and what we've learned.

00:01:25.720 --> 00:01:27.855
And along the way, we'll
do a little demonstration.

00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:35.610
So what we found when we-- the
state of 1805 three years ago,

00:01:35.610 --> 00:01:37.670
was it was a traditional
lecture class

00:01:37.670 --> 00:01:43.390
taught at MIT as a lecture
with a recitation component.

00:01:43.390 --> 00:01:45.740
And the enrollment
was dwindling.

00:01:45.740 --> 00:01:47.240
Students were not taking it.

00:01:47.240 --> 00:01:48.960
They migrated to another class.

00:01:48.960 --> 00:01:52.110
Part of it was that
the faculty who

00:01:52.110 --> 00:01:55.220
were teaching it
were not-- how do

00:01:55.220 --> 00:02:00.130
I say it gently-- were not
so interested in this section

00:02:00.130 --> 00:02:02.090
of undergraduate education.

00:02:02.090 --> 00:02:04.095
And in fact, the
year we took it over,

00:02:04.095 --> 00:02:05.970
I think we were faced--
Haynes can correct me

00:02:05.970 --> 00:02:08.759
if I'm wrong-- with the
choice of either us taking it

00:02:08.759 --> 00:02:12.300
over or not teaching the class.

00:02:12.300 --> 00:02:15.330
So the first year we did
teach it as a lecture class.

00:02:15.330 --> 00:02:17.600
John was the
recitation instructor.

00:02:17.600 --> 00:02:18.690
I was the lecturer.

00:02:18.690 --> 00:02:21.140
And then in the
next two years we

00:02:21.140 --> 00:02:25.900
converted to a fully flipped
classroom, active learning,

00:02:25.900 --> 00:02:28.990
and we co-teach it.

00:02:28.990 --> 00:02:30.570
So what we found is just that.

00:02:30.570 --> 00:02:33.150
Haynes had a big interest
in active learning,

00:02:33.150 --> 00:02:35.630
he's been pushing
them in recitations

00:02:35.630 --> 00:02:40.810
for years with some success I
would say now, it's built up,

00:02:40.810 --> 00:02:45.960
and Davis and everyone is
interested in the world

00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:49.110
of online learning and
what can happen there.

00:02:49.110 --> 00:02:52.310
So we have a component
of the class online.

00:02:52.310 --> 00:02:57.370
The class itself will be put
on OpenCourseWare Educator

00:02:57.370 --> 00:02:58.380
at the end of this year.

00:03:01.090 --> 00:03:02.170
So what did we do?

00:03:02.170 --> 00:03:04.100
We changed everything at once.

00:03:04.100 --> 00:03:07.900
In retrospect, I would
say I don't recommend it.

00:03:07.900 --> 00:03:09.549
But having gotten
through it, you're

00:03:09.549 --> 00:03:12.090
always glad that you did it all
at once, because now we don't

00:03:12.090 --> 00:03:13.400
have to do any of these pieces.

00:03:13.400 --> 00:03:16.107
We can just keep refining them.

00:03:16.107 --> 00:03:17.690
It's a lot to talk
about, so we're not

00:03:17.690 --> 00:03:19.510
going to focus much
on the new curriculum.

00:03:19.510 --> 00:03:21.320
I'll just say a few
words, that we're

00:03:21.320 --> 00:03:25.110
really proud of the
curriculum that we have.

00:03:25.110 --> 00:03:28.600
We've introduced a unit
on Bayesian inference.

00:03:28.600 --> 00:03:35.234
[INAUDIBLE] here is our
Bayesian, can I say zealot?

00:03:35.234 --> 00:03:37.725
Does it say that's your
religion on your Facebook site?

00:03:37.725 --> 00:03:38.391
PROFESSOR 2: No.

00:03:38.391 --> 00:03:38.870
That's me.

00:03:38.870 --> 00:03:40.078
PROFESSOR 1: Oh, that's John.

00:03:42.010 --> 00:03:43.680
That's on John's site.

00:03:43.680 --> 00:03:45.184
John is a convert.

00:03:45.184 --> 00:03:47.660
A Bayesian unit.

00:03:47.660 --> 00:03:49.360
What that has done
for us is allows

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:53.800
us to bridge the gap between
the probability and statistics

00:03:53.800 --> 00:03:55.200
part, which is
always a hard gap.

00:03:55.200 --> 00:03:58.270
Probability I'll say is
a mathematical science.

00:03:58.270 --> 00:04:00.530
Statistic is that
statistics are at least as

00:04:00.530 --> 00:04:02.792
much art as science.

00:04:02.792 --> 00:04:04.250
And so it allows
us to bridge that.

00:04:04.250 --> 00:04:06.970
Bayesian inference
and Bayesian learning

00:04:06.970 --> 00:04:10.930
are becoming more and
more important today.

00:04:10.930 --> 00:04:12.550
So it's good that they see it.

00:04:12.550 --> 00:04:14.670
And finally, even
if they're just

00:04:14.670 --> 00:04:17.130
doctors who need to
know what a p-value is,

00:04:17.130 --> 00:04:19.040
we feel we can explain
the p-value better

00:04:19.040 --> 00:04:20.500
by having introduced this unit.

00:04:20.500 --> 00:04:23.700
So we actually added three weeks
worth of material to the class,

00:04:23.700 --> 00:04:26.340
and we'll talk a little
bit about that later.

00:04:26.340 --> 00:04:29.574
Then we'll speak more
about the pedagogy,

00:04:29.574 --> 00:04:31.740
the importance of the
classroom, and what technology

00:04:31.740 --> 00:04:34.820
we have in the class.

00:04:34.820 --> 00:04:37.190
And now we-- actually
we're going to show you--

00:04:37.190 --> 00:04:40.734
this is a video-- a little bit,
where you should pay attention

00:04:40.734 --> 00:04:42.150
while you're
watching the video is

00:04:42.150 --> 00:04:45.420
the energy in the classroom
and particularly the comments

00:04:45.420 --> 00:04:48.151
and the oohs and aahs that come
at the end when you'll see John

00:04:48.151 --> 00:04:49.400
talking some students on this.

00:04:49.400 --> 00:04:53.000
Today we're going to do
Bayesian updating, which

00:04:53.000 --> 00:04:55.200
is to say we're going to
be using Bayes' theorem

00:04:55.200 --> 00:04:56.370
to learn from data.

00:04:56.370 --> 00:04:58.840
Which treatment would you choose
if you needed a treatment?

00:04:58.840 --> 00:05:02.590
Treatment one cured
100% of the patients.

00:05:02.590 --> 00:05:05.800
Treatment two cured
95% in a trial.

00:05:05.800 --> 00:05:07.820
And treatment three cured 90%.

00:05:07.820 --> 00:05:08.410
All right.

00:05:08.410 --> 00:05:11.420
There's some holdouts
for the 95% cure.

00:05:11.420 --> 00:05:12.420
I'm not sure why.

00:05:12.420 --> 00:05:15.910
What if I gave you
this information.

00:05:15.910 --> 00:05:17.910
Treatment one cured three
out of three patients.

00:05:17.910 --> 00:05:19.740
That's 100%.

00:05:19.740 --> 00:05:22.310
Treatment two cured
19 of 20 patients.

00:05:22.310 --> 00:05:24.450
That's 95%.

00:05:24.450 --> 00:05:26.050
Or you have a standard
treatment which

00:05:26.050 --> 00:05:30.700
has cured 90,000 out of
100,000 patients-- 90%.

00:05:30.700 --> 00:05:35.520
