00:06:53.531 --> 00:06:54.030
OK.

00:06:54.030 --> 00:06:57.220
So what I'm going to go through
here is just what we do.

00:06:57.220 --> 00:06:58.920
I'm going to resist
the urge to talk

00:06:58.920 --> 00:07:00.570
a lot about why
we like doing it,

00:07:00.570 --> 00:07:01.960
because that will come later.

00:07:01.960 --> 00:07:04.230
And John will talk about that.

00:07:04.230 --> 00:07:07.780
The structure is we need
three times 80 minutes.

00:07:07.780 --> 00:07:11.650
So that's 240 minutes,
which matches the five

00:07:11.650 --> 00:07:14.050
times 50 minutes that a
traditional class meets.

00:07:14.050 --> 00:07:16.690
Three lecture hours,
two recitation.

00:07:16.690 --> 00:07:20.440
So it's not more
time, but at all times

00:07:20.440 --> 00:07:25.540
we have two teachers this year
and three assistant teachers

00:07:25.540 --> 00:07:26.230
in the room.

00:07:26.230 --> 00:07:31.350
So there's five instructors
in the room at all times.

00:07:31.350 --> 00:07:32.280
What we have them do.

00:07:32.280 --> 00:07:34.697
Before class, they
do some reading.

00:07:34.697 --> 00:07:36.280
To get them to do
the reading, there's

00:07:36.280 --> 00:07:38.120
reading questions which
they get credit for.

00:07:38.120 --> 00:07:41.970
These are all online,
it's hosted on MITx,

00:07:41.970 --> 00:07:43.310
and they get immediate feedback.

00:07:43.310 --> 00:07:46.290
They know whether they got
the question right or wrong.

00:07:46.290 --> 00:07:49.480
It's possible to ask lots
and lots of different types

00:07:49.480 --> 00:07:52.190
of questions, although we
restrict ourselves mostly

00:07:52.190 --> 00:07:57.480
to multiple choice and fill in
the number type of question.

00:07:57.480 --> 00:08:00.880
Jenny French, who's here, has
done the same thing for 18.03,

00:08:00.880 --> 00:08:05.530
and she's been more ambitious
with the types of questions.

00:08:05.530 --> 00:08:08.260
They come to class and we do
a minimal amount of lecturing.

00:08:08.260 --> 00:08:11.650
What gets left out of a
math class, of our class,

00:08:11.650 --> 00:08:14.590
as opposed to a traditional
class, lecture class, is we

00:08:14.590 --> 00:08:15.892
don't do examples.

00:08:15.892 --> 00:08:17.850
We're going to have the
students work examples,

00:08:17.850 --> 00:08:20.410
and it's much more better--
much more better?--

00:08:20.410 --> 00:08:25.194
much better for students
to work one example than

00:08:25.194 --> 00:08:26.360
for the teacher to work two.

00:08:26.360 --> 00:08:29.320
We feel this strongly.

00:08:29.320 --> 00:08:30.184
You saw that.

00:08:30.184 --> 00:08:31.600
You saw a little
bit of lecturing.

00:08:31.600 --> 00:08:32.200
It was cut.

00:08:32.200 --> 00:08:35.270
I maybe lectured a little more
in the video than you saw,

00:08:35.270 --> 00:08:36.710
but very quickly,
we have them up

00:08:36.710 --> 00:08:38.650
at the boards doing
group problems

00:08:38.650 --> 00:08:43.690
as you saw in the video, while
the teachers and the assistants

00:08:43.690 --> 00:08:45.940
are circulating and
talking to people

00:08:45.940 --> 00:08:48.420
and helping them get
past stumbling points

00:08:48.420 --> 00:08:52.147
and assessing what they're
understanding and correcting

00:08:52.147 --> 00:08:52.772
misconceptions.

00:08:57.300 --> 00:08:59.960
Other components of the class
which you didn't see as much:

00:08:59.960 --> 00:09:02.120
we have whole-class
discussions; we'll

00:09:02.120 --> 00:09:04.950
have them discuss things that
they're tables in groups;

00:09:04.950 --> 00:09:08.220
we can operate on many
levels of interaction

00:09:08.220 --> 00:09:11.410
between students and students,
and students and teachers.

00:09:11.410 --> 00:09:15.090
We also use a little bit of
technology, clicker questions,

00:09:15.090 --> 00:09:17.160
where we'll ask a
multiple choice,

00:09:17.160 --> 00:09:18.920
usually a kind of
concept question

00:09:18.920 --> 00:09:23.800
to see if they've
understood one idea,

00:09:23.800 --> 00:09:26.850
and it also allows us
to take attendance.

00:09:26.850 --> 00:09:29.460
And the students
see it that way.

00:09:29.460 --> 00:09:31.620
Once a week, on
Fridays, we actually

00:09:31.620 --> 00:09:33.750
do a computer
based studio, where

00:09:33.750 --> 00:09:34.850
they have their computers.

00:09:34.850 --> 00:09:38.000
It's the one time we let
them take their computers out

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.560
and we do it in our--
typically we're not

00:09:41.560 --> 00:09:42.860
introducing new material.

00:09:42.860 --> 00:09:45.940
We're doing more advanced
work or simulations

00:09:45.940 --> 00:09:48.360
that you can do on the computer.

00:09:48.360 --> 00:09:51.740
And finally, we do have
traditional problem sets.

00:09:51.740 --> 00:09:55.160
They have to turn in the problem
set on paper once a week,

00:09:55.160 --> 00:09:59.270
and it's graded
in the usual way.

00:09:59.270 --> 00:10:01.190
The pset checker
is not traditional.

00:10:01.190 --> 00:10:04.695
This is something we borrowed
from the physics people.

00:10:04.695 --> 00:10:06.030
Safe is here, I think.

00:10:06.030 --> 00:10:08.105
I think you guys pioneered this.

00:10:08.105 --> 00:10:11.080
It allows the students
to check their answers

00:10:11.080 --> 00:10:16.320
to their homework ahead of time,
which allows us to tell them

00:10:16.320 --> 00:10:18.900
we care about how
you present it,

00:10:18.900 --> 00:10:22.120
that your logic and your
thinking is correct,

00:10:22.120 --> 00:10:24.239
it allows the students--
I can't resist saying

00:10:24.239 --> 00:10:25.530
this one thing's on, I'm sorry.

00:10:25.530 --> 00:10:28.370
It allows the students to
reflect on the piece sets

00:10:28.370 --> 00:10:29.670
as they're doing it.

00:10:29.670 --> 00:10:32.170
One of the things we know is
when we turn back a pset a week

00:10:32.170 --> 00:10:35.319
later, it's gone cold,
they've barely looked at it

00:10:35.319 --> 00:10:36.610
to see what they've done wrong.

00:10:36.610 --> 00:10:41.000
Here they see immediately it's
wrong, and they can reflect.

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:41.500
OK.

00:10:41.500 --> 00:10:46.331
I think now we have an
active part of this.

00:10:46.331 --> 00:10:47.080
John is going to--

00:10:47.080 --> 00:10:49.246
PROFESSOR 2: We believe
strongly in active learning,

00:10:49.246 --> 00:10:51.211
so we got to do some
active learning.

00:10:51.211 --> 00:10:52.960
But really what I want
to take you through

00:10:52.960 --> 00:10:57.200
is how we might envision a
particular new concept being

00:10:57.200 --> 00:10:58.629
introduced to the students.

00:10:58.629 --> 00:11:01.170
What are the various components
and how do they fit together?

00:11:01.170 --> 00:11:03.642
So Jerry mentioned
that we have this unit,

00:11:03.642 --> 00:11:05.850
the middle unit of our
course, on Bayesian inference.

00:11:05.850 --> 00:11:08.475
And the first day we do a number
of problems that involve dice.

00:11:08.475 --> 00:11:10.308
In particular, at the
beginning of the term,

00:11:10.308 --> 00:11:12.080
we actually give
students dice that we

00:11:12.080 --> 00:11:14.210
expect them to keep with
them throughout the term,

00:11:14.210 --> 00:11:15.680
and we use them
to generate data,

00:11:15.680 --> 00:11:18.150
and to do probability
experiments,

00:11:18.150 --> 00:11:20.240
but also just to make
something tangible.

00:11:20.240 --> 00:11:22.701
And so, in particular
on this first day,

00:11:22.701 --> 00:11:25.200
the students will have come in
having done reading, maybe we

00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:27.760
had about 10 pages, they
read, they answer some reading

00:11:27.760 --> 00:11:28.790
questions.

00:11:28.790 --> 00:11:31.610
And this introduces them
to some new concepts,

00:11:31.610 --> 00:11:33.640
but doesn't expect them
to have mastered it.

